        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Beckenham Kent</placeName>
                    <date>June 28 </date>
                    <salute>My dear Lyell</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am greatly obliged to you for having sent me the extract from the American paper.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> How beautiful and true it is, &amp; how well expressed.</p>
<p>It is delightful to see a noble character so well appreciated in a distant land. Again I thank you, and hope that you are pretty well.</p>
<p>Believe me | Your affectionate old pupil | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year has been supplied by the copyist.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The extract has not been found. It probably referred to Lyell’s wife, Mary Elizabeth, who died on 24 April 1873. The copyist has written on the letter ‘after Lady Lyell’s death’.</note>
        </div>        
            
